{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"45e773da-d6d9-4bf5-bd98-3a1293cebaef","content":"\n\nUse **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest** workload versions that match your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update, since your existing workload versions may no longer be compatible.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the **same** versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted installs but won't bring workloads up to date.\n\nAfter updating, verify with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```\n\nIf the build still fails, try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet clean && dotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd5f3811-a50c-4283-a947-4bd03eb5c5fd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a knowledge question, not a code task. I can answer directly:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, matching them to the current SDK version. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Reinstalls the *same* versions of workloads that are already installed. It fixes corrupted installations but doesn't upgrade anything.\n\nSince the issue is that workloads are out of date after an SDK update, `dotnet workload update` is the correct choice.","outputTokens":334},"id":"74ffc4ed-b496-4b62-8c66-b52063e61881","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:47:00.016Z","parentId":"4c053dd5-829b-4fcc-a90c-81c2eac71f59"}
